She flipped to a blank page and noted the date. Below that, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Are you reviving an old memory?" asked Ivory and looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they will let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari out, as he considered her a "blemish." She was born deaf and was the only daughter in the family, her siblings were all boys.
Something similar applied to Ivory as well. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as if the world changed too. As punishment for this difference, Ivory received tasks that required spending most of the time alone.
Moreover, Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't bother Ivory much, since Ivory gained a friend.
"You're going to have a birthday soon, right?" asked Ivory, as she thought about the princess having a birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad flicker in her bright blue eyes.
"Would you like to celebrate your birthday?" asked Ivory, thinking about the last time the princess had answered this question.
"No," tapped Kari. Ivory knew that this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory had been a baby at that time, but remembered how upset the servants and the residents of the city had been. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a beloved queen. And that strangely enough, she could also predict things that then actually came true.
"Well, what would you like to do?" asked Ivory. Kari looked excitedly at Ivory. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
White, various shades of blue
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
"Are you telling me I should get these for you?" asked Ivory, turning to the silent princess, whose braids swung back and forth from her energetic tapping. "Yes?" Ivory chuckled softly. The usually reserved princess showed so much excitement. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! See you later?" asked Ivory, stood up, and slung her way through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her bedsheet.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess had finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things outside her reach, like paint.
Ivory ran through the corridors again and tried to ignore the whispers of the maids.
"I've heard that she's supposed to be possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going into this room."
"I've heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, that's not normal, is it?"
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn't ignore the gossip and continued walking. The royal painter's room was located in the east wing behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Kari's door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons said to have created Frostfell. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual mess. Paint splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered throughout the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Unexpectedly, however, a different scene presented itself. The entire room was clean, and against a background of red velvet stood a chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was currently being painted.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch how your future king is being painted?" asked Aquilo and winked at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," said Ivory, largely ignoring him and gathering the things the silent princess wished for. "I'm only here to get painting supplies."
"My little girl wants to go already?" asked Aquilo. "But I want you to stay!"
"I don't," said Ivory, found the painting supplies on the list and placed them in a box. "Besides, I'm not a girl."
However, the prince had a different opinion. "Oh sweetie, that's just a phase! You'll grow out of it with age!" he said, muffled.
"I have to go," said Ivory and felt uncomfortable because of the prince's answer. Meanwhile, Ivory remembered all the ugly comments he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past. I just want to get away from here.
"You're already leaving?" Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
"That's not proper behavior for a future king!" said Ivory.
"No one will find out. People won't believe you and the painter will stay silent if his life is worth anything to him." He looked at the painter briefly and then leaned closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?" Ivory had been harassed many times in the past, but never by a prince and certainly not by the crown prince.
"Do you actually know what the word 'No' means?" spat Ivory and pushed the crown prince away from her.
"No," answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have anything he wants, doesn't know what the word "No" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have around 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which swirled around in the cold air.
"Come on, get it! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced her to look at him.
